<TEXT>
colorados governor on thursday urged the energy 
department not to reopen rocky flats until it has solved a safety 
problem that left the nuclear weapons plants air ducts clogged 
with 62 pounds of plutonium 
the amount of lost plutonium a deadly carcinogenic poison 
stunned environmentalists monitoring the plant northeast of denver 
rocky flats was shut down by the department of energy late last 
year because of safety and management problems 
i have some comfort that the plant now is shut down gov 
roy romer said thursday and it should not be restarted unless 
they cure this problem the buildup of plutonium in ductwork has 
been known since last summer and the state of colorado has been 
urging doe to take strong action to correct the problem 
doe spokesman pat etchart said late thursday that the department 
will address romers concerns were going to continue to 
evaluate this data 
he said it did not appear the issue would affect the plants 
plutonium processing operations scheduled to resume in june but 
that would be decided as part of the continuing evaluation 
a doe official said wednesday that crews might not finish 
cleaning up the plutoniumclogged air ducts before opening 
i dont know if all the activity will be completed prior to 
restart but if there are any safety questions the energy 
secretary wont order restart catherine kaliniak a department 
of energy spokeswoman said wednesday 
but an environmentalist who has been monitoring the situation 
for the governor says news of the amount of plutonium contamination 
illustrates the need for a review of safeguards against an 
explosion at the plant 
if enough plutonium gathers in one spot it can reach 
criticality the point a nuclear chain reaction could take place 
plant officials have said the amount in the ducts does not threaten 
an accidental chain reaction 
melinda kassen an attorney for the boulderbased environmental 
defense fund had raised questions as a member of gov roy romers 
rocky flats monitoring council about the amount of plutonium in the 
air ducts 
operations should not be restarted until they can make sure 
theyre not going to have those releases in the future ms 
kassen said 
egampg inc the wellesley massbased contractor that operates 
the plant for the federal government gave her the figure of 28 
kilograms or 62 pounds on wednesday that amount is enough to 
build six to seven nuclear bombs but officials said it did not 
pose a threat to workers or residents 
we think the figure of 28 kilograms is pretty solid said 
bill heimbach an egampg spokesman we have a lot more measurements 
to do before we can restart 
egampg had been studying the matter since federal inspectors 
estimated in october that up to 15 kilograms or 33 pounds may be 
in the 4000 feet of glovebox exhaust ducts at the nations only 
plant for making plutonium triggers for nuclear weapons 
technicians handle the deadly radioactive material with gloves 
attached to arm coverings in sealed gloveboxes 
last fall federal inspectors said employees did not maintain 
air filters in the gloveboxes that could have allowed plutonium 
dust to escape into the air ducts the inspectors theorized 
rocky flats the only plant that makes plutonium triggers is 
the target of a criminal probe into allegations of illegal 
hazardous waste handling a federal grand jury has been convened to 
consider evidence gathered in a raid at the plant last june 7 but 
no charges have been handed up 
federal investigators have found a variety of safety and 
management problems at the 16 major facilities in 12 states 
involved in making nuclear weapons and some have led to production 
shutdowns and interruptions 
the problems include a lawsuit by ohio residents who say they 
were harmed by radioactive spills from the fernald plant near 
cincinnati poor training of safety inspectors at the hanford 
nuclear reservation near richland wash and the savannah river 
site near aiken sc and inadequate fire protection at savannah 
river 
</TEXT>
