<TEXT>
a mysterious skin disorder that has 
children in two states scratching the skin off their arms has 
prompted school closings and protests from frustrated parents 
officials said 
the rash which varies from a minor skin irritation to inflamed 
bumps has appeared on the necks arms and backs of students in 
jackson and doddridge counties in west virginia and in mcdowell 
ky officials said wednesday 
were looking for a pattern and we cant establish one said 
loretta haddy an epidemiologist with the west virginia department 
of health unless it really starts getting out of control were 
just assuming its a viral rash 
teacher brenda hamilton of mcdowell where dozens of students 
suffered rashes said the childrens skin looked like theyd been 
scalded with water 
children were literally scratching the skin off their arms 
said james bennett school superintendent in doddridge county in 
northcentral west virginia 
at gilmore elementary school in sandyville in westcentral west 
virginia 50 students reported suffering from the rash according 
to schools superintendent cl staats 
jackson county health department and private doctors who 
examined the children gave different diagnoses staats said 
some said the rash was fifth disease a minor childhood skin 
disorder others classified it as contact dermatitis 
the centers for disease control in atlanta tested blood samples 
taken from the kentucky youths and ruled out fifth disease the 
health officials said last week 
jackson and doddridge counties are not adjacent to each other 
neither is adjacent to mcdowell in eastern kentucky near the west 
virginia border 
parents kept more than 450 elementary and high school students 
home on tuesday in mcdowell and about 40 people held a protest 
over officials inability to identify the rash which first 
appeared in the small town march 12 
protest leader brenda cook 34 said parents were afraid because 
no one knew anything about the rash or its longterm effect she 
said they wanted the school closed until the problem has been 
identified 
its something in the air or inside that school cook said 
jane bond a health adviser for the floyd county health 
department said its upsetting the parents but we really dont 
have any answers for them yet 
examinations in west virginia showed no pattern and gave no 
indication the school environment was causing the rash said herb 
loy director of immunization for the west virginia department of 
health 
gilmore elementary school was closed friday so that biological 
and environmental testing could be done to see if the school was 
causing the problem staats said 
it is expected to remain closed for at least two weeks pending 
the release of the test results he said 
in doddridge county officials said 20 fourthgraders at big 
isaac elementary school broke out in rashes in january and february 
most of the children are back to normal but have been moved to 
the school gymnasium to isolate them from others bennett said 
