industrial areas of thuringia and saxony where zwickau is located 
west german flags waving from the windows of the citys aging 
apartment buildings show which way the wind is blowing 
but as west german companies rush to get a foothold in the 
eastern market trabant workers realize their economys immediate 
future is uncertain 
my friends and i expect a dry spell of 23 years says 
engineer dieter hildesheim 35 then things will look up again 
sales of the little car are plummeting because east germans are 
waiting for economic union with west germany planned by this 
summer so they can buy a car of their choice 
volkswagen production is expected to reach full steam only in 
1994 so sachsenring hopes its revamped trabant with a vw engine 
will sell in eastern europe and canada in the meantime 
its a far cry from east germanys closed market last year 
which buyers faced waits of 15 years or more for a trabi and the 
plant advertised 700 openings 
trabis now are available for immediate delivery the giant job 
notice board at a plant entrance is conspicuously empty 
dieter voigt chief of the state vehicle building conglomerate 
ifa has said up to 70 percent of the workers in the automotive and 
supply industries about 100000 people could lose their jobs in 
the switch to a freemarket economy 
guenter noetzold an economist at leipzig university predicts 2 
million east germans a quarter of the labor force will be jobless 
for a limited period 
but blank who has a wife and two children is convinced east 
germans will find enough work in rebuilding their land after 
decades of neglect 
because of the mess for example in road and housing 
construction there will be jobs he says 
however some zwickau residents do not hide their bitterness and 
sense of helplessness 
henry hofmann a lifetime employee knows hell be among 5000 
sachsenring employees volkswagen is expected to dump 
the 33yearold engineer is in charge of making the trabants 
hard plastic body panels well all have to search for new 
