<TEXT>
a new study concludes that airline 
deregulation has brought higher fares more danger and less 
service and recommends a federal commission to regulate all modes 
of transportation 
the report published wednesday by the liberal economic policy 
institute called for price setting within a range that would 
prevent airlines from overcharging in thin markets or undercharging 
to drive out competitors on heavily traveled routes 
the study called for airlines to be limited to one hub operation 
to avoid a system that its author paul stephen dempsey said has 
destroyed the inherent advantages of the air transport system 
dempsey said it is cheaper to take a taxi from kansas city to 
st louis than to fly at full fare and that many flights take much 
longer than they did several years ago because so many pass through 
hub airports 
the time has come to reconsider the experiment of airline 
deregulation said dempsey a university of denver professor who 
supported deregulation in the late 1970s when he was a lawyer for 
the nowdefunct civil aeronautics board 
dempseys study challenged reports by the transportation 
department and the airline industry that hail deregulation as a 
boon to travelers 
the phenomenon of jet lag has been replaced by the phenomenon 
of hub lag said dempsey he referred to the formation of hub 
airports where a single airline dominates flights decreasing 
competition and increasing fares on some routes 
the report said deregulation has increased airlines fares for 
the average traveler by 26 cents per mile over prices they likely 
would be paying without it the cost per trip may be as much as 33 
percent higher and is likely to take longer dempsey said at a news 
conference releasing the study flying blind the failure of 
airline deregulation 
the crux of the reports economic conclusion is that airline 
ticket prices had been declining for several years before 
deregulation but the decline slowed after the government stopped 
regulating fares 
federal aviation administrator james b busey responding to a 
question about dempseys report at a separate news conference 
wednesday said deregulation has provided increased access to the 
air traffic system for millions of americans 
he said the us system is the safest in the world 
if people are upset about the rates theyre paying then 
demand is going to control that busey said encouraging 
competition in a deregulated market is the best way to lower 
rates 
the institute study says that of the 514 nonhub communities 
with air service before deregulation 312 have suffered declines in 
flight frequency while 143 lost all service 
the institute study says complaints filed against us airlines 
skyrocketed from 7326 in 1983 to 40985 in 1987 and cited a poll 
of pilots that said 97 percent believe deregulation has made flying 
more dangerous 
it also said the number of nearcollisions soared from 311 in 
1982 to 1058 in 1987 that the average age of pilots has decreased 
while the age of planes has gone up and that spending for 
maintenance has declined 
dempsey acknowledged that fatalities and accidents have 
declined but he credited that to safety improvements by 
manufacturers rather than airlines which he said are treating 
their aircraft worse not better 
</TEXT>
