president bush takes about four times longer 
than john kennedy to fill his administrations top jobs but much 
of the delay is because of ethics laws snooping reporters and 
yes politics a presidential scholar says 
we find ourselves with a presidential appointment process 
that greatly complicates and elongates the change in policy 
directions that democratic elections are designed to permit g 
calvin mackenzie wrote in the april issue of government executive 
magazine 
procedural changes new legislation escalating media scrutiny 
and more complex politics have all slowed the appointment 
process said mackenzie a professor of government at colby 
college in waterville maine 
the bush administration has survived this process because it 
took over a friendly government and brought no great agenda for 
change said the author but the consequences of this new 
complexity would not have been viewed with such equanimity if a 
democrat had won in 1988 nor will they be so viewed in future 
transitions where the government changes hands from one party to 
another 
the time it takes to fill a position by presidential appointment 
and senate confirmation has lengthened steadily since the 
administration of president kennedy wrote mackenzie director of 
the presidential appointee project of the national academy of 
public administration 
after kennedys election in 1960 it took 238 months for the 
average appointee to a highranking job to be confirmed by the 
senate mackenzie wrote in bushs case it will be more than eight 
months 
figures for other presidents who entered the white house by 
election during the period were 339 months for nixon 455 months 
for carter and 530 months for reagan 
the figures were based on a study of 964 nominees during the 
five administrations covering more than half of the appointments 
to positions at the assistant secretary or deputy director level or 
above in departments and major agencies 
mackenzie said that the white house does not deserve all the 
blame it has received for the slowdown 
both the reagan and bush transitions have been slowed by the 
impact of the ethics in government act of 1978 and subsequent 
efforts to tighten even further the regulations of the actions and 
personal finances of executive branch officials he wrote 
the article said an increasing amount of time is taken up 
explaining the rules to potential appointees completing and 
reviewing financial disclosure forms and altering investment 
portfolios to avoid conflicts of interest 
