missing voices who should be given special consideration in 
awarding broadcast station licenses 
ms polivy represents rainbow broadcasting co which was 
awarded a tv license in orlando fla a rival metro broadcasting 
inc argued unsuccessfully before a federal appeals court that it 
was denied the license unfairly 
gregory guillot metros lawyer said the fccs affirmative 
action program is a complete total failure he said the policy 
has increased minority ownership of television and radio stations 
by only 1 percent in 18 years 
the connecticut case is a test of the socalled distress sale 
provisions of the fcc rules which allow a broadcaster faced with 
the loss of its license to sell to a minorityowned business at 75 
percent of market value 
alan shurberg who is white appealed the award of a hartford tv 
station to hispanicled astroline communications co 
the federal communications commission adopted the rules in 1972 
and strengthened them in 1978 the fcc under reaganera chairman 
mark s fowler tried to rewrite the rules but congress said no in 
1987 
the distress sale provisions were struck down in march 1989 on 
constitutional grounds by a threejudge panel of the us court of 
appeals in washington but less than a month later another 
threejudge panel of the same court upheld the minority and female 
preference provisions 
the fcc now is defending the rules it had tried to scrap 
the commission maintains that by regulating the ownership of 
broadcast outlets the government will have an indirect impact on 
program diversity and thereby serve the public interest 
daniel m armstrong fcc associate general counsel told the 
court the fcc doesnt exactly know how minority ownership 
translates into more diverse views but the agency believes it does 
in subtle ways such as through news and public affairs programs 
