germany 
the talks came hours before the groups that toppled the old 
communist order were to rally throughout the country protesting 
the new leaderships alleged ties to the secret police of the 
ousted communist regime 
lothar de maiziere leader of the christian democratled 
coalition that finished first in the balloting said he was 
optimistic that a government could be formed with the rival social 
democrats 
during a visit in the west german city of stuttgart on 
wednesday de maiziere said that a new governing coalition could be 
formed within the next two weeks 
however the social democrats who finished a distant second in 
the march 18 balloting have expressed concern about whether they 
will be able to work with some of the more conservative elements of 
de maizieres alliance 
the social democrats also favor a more gradual process for 
unification than the christian democrats 
we expect to learn where the conversations will lead markus 
meckel a social democrat leader told reporters before talks began 
today in east berlin 
new forum which led the revolt last fall that brought down the 
government of communist leader erich honecker called for the 
demonstrations to force an immediate investigation of new 
parliament members 
in bonn members of west german chancellor helmut kohls junior 
coalition partners the free democrats joined with the opposition 
social democrats in rejecting a kohl government proposal to grant 
amnesty to former members of the east german secret police 
wrongs cannot be allowed to be swept under the table 
gerhard baum deputy chairman of the free democrats said wednesday 
voting in their first free elections march 18 east germans 
overwhelmingly elected a threeparty coalition that favors quick 
unification with west germany and a capitalist economy 
de maiziere who heads the winning coalition and ibrahim 
boehme head of the social democrats both were accused after the 
elections of having ties to the former secret police 
both men denied the accusations similar charges have been 
raised against other members of the newly elected 400member 
parliament 
the 85000member secret police known as the stasi and its 
109000 informers were used by east germanys hardline stalinist 
government for decades to control the countrys citizens the unit 
was disbanded after honecker was overthrown 
west german interior minister wolfgang schaeuble said tuesday 
that a generous amnesty for the stasi may be needed to quell 
further instability in east germany 
not everyone who was forced to report to the stasi was a 
criminal schaeuble said kohl later told reporters he agreed 
in principle with the proposal 
in the east german elections kohl backed the coalition led by 
de maiziere 
baum said former stasi members should be allowed to begin new 
careers but it is out of the question to allow them to hold 
important political posts 
boehme temporarily stepped down from his party post until his 
name was cleared of any stasi links lawmaker horst ehmke a leader 
of west germanys social democratic party on wednesday called on 
de maiziere to also resign 
in the meantime a reformoriented communist government that 
replaced the ousted honecker government continues to handle daily 
operations of the country the retooled communist party was soundly 
defeated in the elections 
on wednesday an east german prosecutor said that doctors will 
decide if honecker is physically and mentally able to face charges 
of corruption and abuse of power 
lothar reuter east germanys deputy chief prosecutor told the 
official news agency adn that medical specialists also will examine 
other aging officials accused of misusing their power during the 
honecker regime 
the comments further increase the likelihood that the ailing 
honecker who ruled east germany with the help of the secret police 
for 17 years may avoid criminal trial 
authorities already have decided this week not to charge 
honecker 77 and in poor health with conspiracy and high treason 
</TEXT>
