<TEXT>
single people in the nations secondlargest 
city suffer widespread and often illegal bias ranging from rental 
discrimination to restricted hospital visits it was reported today 
the alleged bias against unmarried people in los angeles was 
documented by the citys consumer task force on marital status and 
reflects a national trend the los angeles times reported 
city attorney james k hahn declined to comment on the 126page 
report until it was formally released later today 
most of us arent living in traditional american families 
anymore and the rights and privileges extended to a few should be 
extended to everyone hahn said when he created the task force in 
october 1989 
according to the newspaper the report details alleged 
discriminatory practices that include landlords who refuse to rent 
to single people or unmarried couples auto insurers that levy 
higher premiums or refuse policies for singles and airlines that 
restrict the sharing of frequentflier awards to spouses or blood 
relatives 
most of these practices are illegal in california said 
thomas f coleman a family law expert and chairman of the task 
force 
discrimination based on marital status is arbitrary 
inappropriate illegal and unfair but it is also a pervasive 
national problem coleman said 
our report represents the emergence of a new dimension of the 
consumer protection movement he said call it singles 
rights 
the report also noted that singles are often charged higher 
health club dues than married people and can be denied hospital 
bedside visits that are sometimes limited to spouses or family 
members 
the task force report is the result of three public hearings 
where about 30 witnesses including business representatives legal 
experts and politicians testified about alleged discrimination 
the single divorced separated and widowed collectively make up 
55 percent of people 15 years or older said coleman 
</TEXT>
