<TEXT>
soviet citizens are split down the middle on 
whether government should be responsible for peoples wellbeing or 
individuals should be responsible for themselves a new poll finds 
a poll of 2500 soviets also found that the minority group a 
person belongs to not age education or communist party 
membership governs soviet thought on many issues 
the poll released wednesday by former president jimmy carters 
public policy center found 46 percent of respondents favored the 
traditional communist idea that the state is responsible for 
people 45 percent said responsibility fell to individuals 
many of those who want rapid change to solve social problems 
also hold the state responsible for individual wellbeing wrote 
ada finifter a michigan state university political science 
professor in a summary of the findings the fact that so many 
others believe in individual responsibility makes it likely that 
there will be shifting and unstable majorities for various reform 
efforts she said 
the national center for public opinion research in moscow helped 
direct the poll with american researchers from the university of 
pennsylvania michigan state and the atlantabased carter center 
which is affiliated with emory university 
pollsters conducted 90minute interviews with 2485 soviet 
citizens in their homes last november and december carter who 
commented briefly as the poll was presented called it the first 
ever definitive poll conducted in the soviet union 
the soviet union covers about half of europe and 40 percent of 
asia russianspeaking people live in every part of the country but 
are just one of more than 100 national groups they make up only 
about 53 percent of the population 
the pollsters said deep divisions among ethic groups could spell 
trouble for those seeking change 
there is no question that the policies and reforms that will 
be implemented have to be so crafted as to take into account 
the fact that on the most fundamental and deeply felt questions 
the peoples of the soviet union inhabit vastly different worlds 
wrote ellen mickiewicz a carter center fellow and political 
science professor at emory 
the poll found that only 1 percent of the baltic residents but 
29 percent of russians said the soviet army always acted in the 
interests of the people since the poll was taken one of the 
baltic republics lithuania has proclaimed its independence 
communist party membership did not guarantee support of party 
policies the poll found only 25 percent of party members polled 
expressed full confidence in the party and 12 percent expressed no 
confidence party members were somewhat more supportive of rapid 
change than nonmembers the pollsters said 
forty percent said organized religion always acted in their best 
interests and 7 percent said it never does but 38 percent gave no 
answer among soviet georgians who include a heavy moslem 
minority 69 percent gave high marks to religion 
nationwide 54 percent said they support free speech even at the 
cost of political disorder 37 percent said public order should be 
more important only 11 percent of the respondents said they agreed 
with the old order precept of strict income equality 84 
percent want to permit varying incomes 
pollsters said that because some soviet polling methods differ 
from those in the united states no margin of error was assigned to 
the study 
