<TEXT>
congress is moving toward sweetening an 
already sweet loan deal for israel by slashing millions of dollars 
in fees the united states has always charged other countries 
israel supporters easily won concessions in the house and senate 
on wednesday to lower or eliminate fees normally charged borrowers 
who take advantage of a ussubsidized housing loan program 
the concessions are the first of their kind in the programs 
30year history 
as part of a supplemental money bill that was going before the 
full house today israel would be able to arrange 400 million in 
private loans to build housing for the thousands of soviet jews now 
emigrating under moscows newly loosened policies 
repayment of the loans is to be guaranteed by the us treasury 
making them less risky and therefore obtainable at a lower than 
normal interest rate 
the house foreign affairs committee on wednesday approved a 
provision sponsored by rep howard berman dcalif that would 
allow the united states to charge a maximum loan origination fee of 
onefourth of 1 percent of the loan amount rather than the 1 
percent charged all other borrowers in the program that would save 
israel 3 million 
in addition bermans language would let the government charge 
israel no more than 150000 a year over the life of the 30year 
loan to service the account instead of the normal fee of onehalf 
of 1 percent of the outstanding balance that would save another 
185 million the first year and slightly declining amounts in 
later years 
acting on similar legislation the senate foreign relations 
committee was even more generous it set the same limit on 
origination fees but waived annual service charges entirely 
israel last used the housing guarantee program in the 1970s 
when it obtained eight separate 25 million loans it has paid the 
full fees on those loans said peter kimm of the agency for 
international development who has administered the program for 
most of its 30year life 
but israel supporters successfully argued that the unusually 
large size of the current loan the largest ever under the program 
and israels excellent repayment record entitle it to special 
treatment 
kimm likened the fees to what any homebuyer pays for mortgage 
insurance a sort of risk pool which helps defray the costs to the 
treasury of making good on defaulted loans overall program fees 
will generate about 10 million this year on outstanding loans of 
about 15 billion he said 
even with the fees the loan would be a good deal for israel he 
said 
the borrower gets a loan he could not otherwise obtain under 
far more favorable conditions including a lower interest rate 
he said thats a very good business deal for the borrower and 
theyre anxious to do so even with the fees he said 
in addition to the financial benefits israel also will receive 
waivers of several normal requirements of the program including 
some oversight and a stipulation that 90 percent of housing built 
is targeted to people with belowmedian incomes 
the bush administration has been lukewarm to the loan 
guarantees saying it could accept them only if israel promises not 
to use the money to settle jewish emigres in the disputed occupied 
territories 
israel is the largest recipient of us foreign aid receiving 
3 billion a year in military and economic support in addition 
the us ally receives hundreds of millions of dollars worth of 
other special benefits largely because of its clout with congress 
 
