<TEXT>
the deltawinged pegasus 
rocket designed to put small satellites in orbit after launch from 
an aircraft will have its first flight next week the defense 
department said 
if all goes well the 41000pound rocket will be strapped under 
a b52 and taken to 40000 feet for launch wednesday over the 
militarys western test range according to the pentagons defense 
advanced research projects agency 
the 440pound launch payload dubbed pegsat will be placed in a 
polar orbit of 368 miles 
pegsat will release a small experimental navy communications 
satellite agency spokeswoman jan bodanyi said wednesday 
remaining on the pegsat frame will be an instrument package to 
send data back to scientists about the stress on pegasus and its 
payload as it goes through the atmosphere and into space bodanyi 
said 
two canisters designed to release chemicals to produce an 
artificial northern lights effect also will be aboard 
barium mixed with a small amount of strontium will be released 
over central canada shortly after sunset to allow national 
aeronautics and space administration scientists to study the 
resulting glowing space cloud to learn more about the earths 
magnetosphere and ionosphere 
pegasus developed by virginiabased orbital sciences corp and 
delawarebased hercules aerospace corp is designed to put small 
satellites into orbit cheaply 
the pentagon and nasa want to use pegasus for military and 
science satellites but pegasus also is expected to attract 
business from companies foreign governments and university 
scientists who need a cheap way to put small payloads in orbit 
an orbital science corp official estimated the cost of a 
pegasus launch at between 6 million and 8 million depending on 
how much business it gets 
