<TEXT>
the chemist who said he discovered a way to 
produce nuclear fusion in a lab jar said the overwhelmingly 
negative response to his work from other researchers has shaken his 
faith in science 
stanley pons commented wednesday as the british journal nature 
published a highly critical analysis of his discovery in todays 
edition that was based on measurements by his university of utah 
colleagues 
pons galvanized the science world a year ago when he and a 
colleague announced that they had achieved cold fusion such a 
feat if true would give the world a limitless supply of energy 
two months after last springs announcement michael h salamon 
a physicist at the university who was uninvolved in the research 
set up sensors in pons lab for five weeks to check the nuclear 
output of his cold fusion equipment 
we did not see a peep salamon said in an interview there 
was not an iota not a sniff of conventional fusion occurring we 
saw no neutrons or gamma rays that could be attributed to a fusion 
process 
pons responded that salamons experiment was poorly performed 
and done to please physicists at other universities who were 
unhappy that such an important discovery had been made by a 
chemist not a physicist 
its pretty distressing because most of the allegations in 
the paper are not true pons said in an interview 
he said the physicists ignored energy cells in his lab that were 
producing large amounts of heat and instead set up their monitoring 
equipment to check ones that were making only low amounts he said 
the sensors were also placed at an angle that missed evidence of 
nuclear activity 
they were in the lab for political reasons said pons 
they were embarrassed by this they were embarrassed that a 
chemist had fallen into a nuclear reaction so simply their outside 
colleagues were putting tremendous pressure on them 
pons again defended his research in his remarks today at the 
opening session of a threeday cold fusion conference in salt lake 
city he said more than 200 experiments involving 2000 
measurements have produced excess heat that can only be the result 
of nuclear fusion 
indeed he said a few experiments generated twice the energy 
output that you would expect in a watercooled nuclear fission 
reactor 
on wednesday pons also accused nature of trying to undermine 
his work by publishing negative studies while ignoring supporting 
evidence 
a series of critical editorials in the prestigious journal has 
been part of a drumbeat of unfavorable publicity much of it 
occurring after other scientists could not duplicate pons results 
its strange to me that if people totally disbelieve it why 
do they persist pons asked why dont they leave us alone and 
let us get on with our work are they afraid something is going 
on 
pons said he has lost a year of research because of the need to 
duplicate his initial findings to try to answer the skeptics 
its overwhelming you cant work scientifically in an 
atmosphere like this pons said my confidence in science is 
shaken 
however he said he plans soon to publish three massive 
papers covering heat output from cold fusion in which we hope 
to set the record straight 
others saw the latest report in nature as one more reason to 
doubt claims about cold fusion 
its another nail in the coffin commented ronald parker 
director of the plasma fusion center at massachusetts institute of 
technology they did a very careful search for fusion effects 
and they came up empty 
pons equipment consists of a palladium electrode wrapped in 
platinum and immersed in a flask of deuterium oxide or heavy 
water when electricity is run through the metals proponents say 
deuterium atoms fuse giving off more heat than the energy put in 
nuclear fusion is the reaction that powers the stars 
traditionally scientists have believed that fusion could occur only 
at extremely high temperatures 
</TEXT>
