three people charged with trying to smuggle 
devices for triggering nuclear weapons to iraq appeared in court 
today and two were ordered held without bond until a later hearing 
british authorities also said they were investigating the 
alleged smuggling of naval equipment to iraq but few details were 
released one news report said documents had been seized in two 
british cities and that arrests were expected 
in san diego today an indictment opened in us district court 
charged five people and two britishbased companies with illegally 
exporting electrical components that could be used in the 
detonation of nuclear warheads two of the five people indicted in 
san diego were arrested in london on wednesday 
iraq today denied any involvement in the alleged attempt to 
smuggle the usmade nuclear weapons devices iraq also told 
britains envoy in baghdad that it reserves the right to acquire 
any advanced technology it wants 
president saddam hussein of iraq told a rally in baghdad that 
enemies of the arabs were trying to hinder iraqs march of 
progress he did not specifically mention britain or the 
smuggling case 
