<TEXT>
authorities on thursday arrested a 
retired deputy interior minister who ran a camp in northern 
bulgaria in which hundreds of prisoners may have been killed during 
todor zhivkovs regime 
the arrest of 80yearold gen mincho spassov followed a series 
of reports about the camp that have stirred memories of stalinist 
repression 
the arrest tersely reported by the state news agency came a 
day after spassov told the communist party daily rabotnichesko delo 
that he visited the camp in lovech only once 
the military prosecutors office said it was holding spassov in 
connection with events at lovech and another camp near sofia and 
on charges of aiding and abetting embezzlement when he was head of 
the communist party office overseeing foreign travel 
the communist party daily meanwhile quoted a former guard at the 
lovech camp tsvyatko goranov as saying spassov visted lovech once 
or twice a week during the period from 1959 to 1962 
he would always tell us work them to death recalled the 
guard he said windows have been smashed at his home and graffiti 
reading living butcher daubed on his walls since the 
disclosures about lovech began to emerge 11 days ago 
the reports in staterun and independent media are part of a 
general probe of the past since zhivkov bulgarias stalinist 
leader for 35 years was ousted in november 
tales of how zhivkov and his fellow communists jailed and 
sometimes murdered political opponents have come into the open 
but none of the reports has been so shocking to bulgarians as 
those about lovech where hundreds of prisoners were reported 
clubbed to death tied in sacks and even fed to pigs at a nearby 
camp 
the disclosures could add to eventual charges against zhivkov 
who is being held pending an investigation of his actions 
spassov told rabotnichesko delo that zhivkov must have known 
about the torture everybody knew he said 
but until march 18 when a popular sunday news program broke the 
story of lovech most bulgarians did not know the torture and 
murder at lovech had been chronicled only in a secret 1962 report 
for the top echelons of the communist party 
president petar mladenov and other top communists have now 
called for investigations by the prosecutorgeneral into the doings 
at lovech and other camps and prisons which were run by the 
interior ministry 
meanwhile rabotnichesko delo the independent daily 
demokratsiya and tv have brought new reports each day 
an exconvict bozhidar petrov telling of his 14 months in 
hell in lovech from jan 1961 to march 1962 charged in one 
newspaper interview that about 1000 prisoners died in the camp 
another former prisoner valter vasilev put the death toll at 
300 in his account of lovech in rabotnichesko delo a capt gazdov 
said to have been one of the three security officers running the 
camp says about 150 people died 
petrov said prisoners faced daily torture if they did not meet 
the nearimpossible work quotas set at the camp wounds from daily 
beatings were left untreated and festered so badly that worms 
crawled in them he claimed 
at least two prisoners were driven to suicide by the cruelty 
petrov told demokratsiya 
the accounts about lovech mark another stage in bulgarias 
gradual break with its stalinist past 
after the hungarian uprising in 1956 bulgarias worried 
communist leadership began rounding up political prisoners petrov 
said one camp inmate who died at lovech while he was there was a 
sofia violin player imprisoned for telling a joke 
torture and murder at lovech and possibly at other camps 
appear to have peaked in the late 1950s and early 1960s the 
cultural thaw and destalinization in the soviet union under 
nikita s khrushchev at that time apparently prompted zhivkov to 
close the camps 
