<TEXT>
a house subcommittee voted thursday to 
continue the peanut price support program virtually intact for 
another five years after talks among industry groups seeking 
changes broke down 
the bill would allow the 631 per ton support price for 
domesticuse peanuts to increase up to 6 percent a year as the cost 
of production increases 
the bush administration had proposed a 20 percent reduction in 
the support price and the elimination of the annual price escalator 
however debate in the agriculture subcommittee on tobacco and 
peanuts focused on negotiations that have been going on for months 
between peanut growers and manufacturers 
rep charles hatcher dga who initiated the talks said the 
effort to reach a compromise failed when growers outside of georgia 
refused to accept demands from manufacturers in three major areas 
the manufacturers he said wanted the support price adjusted 
every two years instead of annually although they agreed to a 
biennial increase of up to 12 percent 
they also insisted on changes dealing with peanut quality and 
regulatory complexity hatcher said and they demanded creation of 
a committee of representatives from all segments of the industry to 
advise the secretary of agriculture on peanut regulations 
hatcher said georgia growers who produce 45 percent of the 
nations peanuts were willing to accept the manufacturers demands 
in exchange for their support to continue the supply management 
program with a 631 per ton support price and a price escalation 
clause 
but other grower groups would not agree he said and unless a 
compromise can be reached in the next few weeks peanut growers 
face a potential repeat of the 1981 and 1985 farm bill debates 
when manufactuers tried to kill the peanut program on the house 
floor 
peanuts and tobacco are the only commodities in which the 
government price support program is based on a supply management 
concept 
the secretary of agriculture each year determines the volume of 
peanuts needed to meet domestic demand then divides that quota 
among farmers who produced peanuts for domestic use in previous 
years 
farmers with government quotas are guaranteed the 631 per ton 
support price while other peanut farmers who produce for the 
export market are guaranteed about 150 a ton for their peanuts 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

