<DOCNO> AP900329-0112 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the centers for disease control said today its 
longawaited study of agent orange shows vietnam veterans at 
increased risk of only one type of cancer and no evidence 
that the risk stems from exposure to the dangerous herbicide used 
in the war 
the study which had been criticized by veterans groups even 
before it was released focused on vietnam veterans and cancer and 
only indirectly evaluated agent orange exposure the cdc said 
but it added that the cancer risk among the vets in the study 
seemed to be the opposite of the pattern for use of agent 
orange veterans who served on navy ships were somewhat more 
likely to get cancer than those who served on land and veterans 
who served in the region of heaviest agent orange use were at 
somewhat lower risk than others the cdc said 
agent orange sprayed by the us military to remove jungle and 
crops in vietnam contained dioxin a highly toxic chemical that 
some studies have found to increase the risk of cancer 
the cdc study conducted over five years surveyed male cancer 
patients who were the right age to have served in vietnam whether 
they did serve or not they were compared with a group of similar 
males with no history of cancer 
the patients medical records were examined for six kinds of 
cancer including soft tissue cancer and similar sarcomas a group 
of cancers which the cdc concedes has been of great concern among 
vietnam veterans 
vietnam vets were found to be at a roughly 50 percent increased 
risk for nonhodgkins lymphoma a relatively rare cancer of 
the lymphatic system the cdc said 
the study did not find any evidence that the increased risk 
might be due to agent orange exposure said cdc director william 
l roper 
there was no evidence the cdc reported that 
nonhodgkins lymphoma was more likely to develop in one group of 
vietnam veterans than in another 
specifically the yearly risk of nonhodgkins lymphoma is about 
one in 10000 for men 35 to 59 the age group of most vietnam vets 
the risk for vietnam vets is about 15 per 10000 roper said 
but the cdc found no increased risk for sarcomas usually 
cancers of the bodys connective tissues or for other cancer types 
the veterans administration has been awaiting the study before 
making its decision on whether to award benefits to veterans 
exposed to agent orange nearly 35000 claims have been filed 
citing the chemical as a cause of disabilities including cancer 
skin disease and miscarriages by veterans wives 
veterans secretary edward j derwinski said today that based on 
the study he would order compensation paid to veterans suffering 
from nonhodgkins lymphoma 
derwinski in announcing the move in washington mentioned only 
the link between vietnam service and the lymphoma he did not say 
the connection was because of agent orange 
his announcement speeds up va action on the findings the agency 
had said it would submit the study to a review panel 
american legion officials told their vietnam veteran members in 
advance of todays announcement that they should not be too 
optimistic about this study which was mandated by congress 
the government has ducked the issue of agent orange for more 
than a dozen years said the legions national commander miles 
s epling we are tired of waiting for more studies especially 
irrelevant ones 
the legion has accused cdc of ignoring military records that 
could have produced a more detailed study 
the cdc study found that the risk of nonhodgkins lymphoma was 
nearly double 90 percent higher for navy veterans stationed on 
ocean ships than for nonveterans that was the only statistically 
significant risk for any branch of service said dr daniel a 
hoffman assistant director for science at the cdcs center for 
environmental health 
for all veterans the 50 percent higher risk of that type of 
cancer is what epidemiologists call a weak association hoffman 
said while statistically significant anything less than a 
twofold increase can sometimes be caused by other factors he 
said 
the cdc study did not suggest reasons for the increased risk for 
one cancer over another or for the increased risk among navy 
sailors at sea 
the study did not include blood tests to determine the actual 
amount of dioxin that might remain in the cancer patients 
bloodstream two decades or more after military service 
hoffman said such tests were not a practical way to determine 
dioxin exposure because it is possible that test findings might be 
tainted by the patients illness itself 
</TEXT>
