<TEXT>
the nations most widely circulated medical 
journal is moving its release date to wednesday from friday giving 
it a oneday jump on a prestigious rival but the rivals editor 
says we dont feel threatened 
the journal of the american medical association says the main 
reasons for its publishing earlier in the week are improved 
production capabilities a desire to release important findings 
quickly and a wish to give news reporters more time at weeks end 
to develop spinoff stories the change begins next week 
but if you read the ama press release carefully they want 
to come out first before the new england journal of medicine 
said dr arnold relman editor of the bostonbased new england 
journal which publishes on thursday 
i cant understand any other reason beyond the obvious 
competitive one relman added in a telephone interview wednesday 
dr george lundberg editor of jama acknowledged in a news 
release announcing the change last month i want jama to be 
poised to be able to publish new research findings before other 
medical and scientific journals 
but lundberg maintained on thursday that competition is a lesser 
motive 
lundberg said though articles appearing each week in the new 
england journal and in jama are independent of each other they do 
cover overlapping subjects occasionally 
in such instances we would prefer our authors to have an 
earlier publication date than theirs lundberg said 
we at jama value media coverage greatly because one of our 
basic missions is to educate the public to lead healthier lives 
both journals are heavily covered by the media and their 
release dates have more to do with determining when their contents 
reach airwaves and newspapers than when they reach physicians 
jama published by the chicagobased ama the nations largest 
organization of doctors has a regular englishlanguage circulation 
of 293000 including the amas more than 290000 members the 
journal also has 290000 copies going overseas each week in 12 
languages lundberg said 
the 178yearold new england journal the nations oldest 
medical journal is published by the massachusetts medical society 
it has a circulation of about 230000 including 10000 society 
members and about 50000 overseas subscribers relman said 
though it is smaller the new england journal carries the 
hottest articles said david pendlebury of the 
philadelphiabased institute for scientific information the 
institute tracks how many times articles in 3200 journals 
worldwide are subsequently cited in published research 
pendlebury said a study about a year ago indicated that the 100 
mostcited articles in life sciences in the previous year included 
nine from the new england journal and three from jama 
we dont feel threatened by a change in their publication 
day relman said it seems to me that the content of what is 
published is vastly more important than the day of the week on 
which it is published 
dr aran ron assistant to the medical director at beth israel 
medical center in new york city and a reader of both journals 
agreed though for different reasons 
i think that jama has more general interesttype articles and 
covers ground a little wider while the the new england journal has 
more scientific specialty and indepth articles ron said 
i dont perceive a big competition from my perspective for the 
two added ron who has had research published in jama i think 
they serve different purposes 
</TEXT>
