<TEXT>
an immigration law passed four years ago to 
stem the flow of illegal aliens across the southern border of the 
united states has caused widespread hiring discrimination the 
general accounting office reported thursday 
gao believes many employers discriminated because the laws 
verification system does not provide a simple or reliable method to 
verify job applicants eligibility to work said the report from 
the congressional agency 
the report triggered calls on capitol hill for repeal of the 
laws civil and criminal penalties or sanctions for employers 
who hire illegal aliens 
immigration and naturalization service commissioner gene mcnary 
rejected those calls describing the report as soft and 
hedged 
as many as 10 percent of the 46 million employers considered 
under the gao survey may be discriminating based on national 
origins because of confusion over the 1986 immigration reform and 
control act the report said 
discrimination related to the law is widespread and 
serious but not pervasive according to the 162page report 
employers discriminate because the laws verification system 
does not provide a simple or reliable method to verify job 
applicants eligibility to work the report said 
it indicated that those who do the hiring are uncertain about 
just which applicants they may hire and discriminate lest they 
incur federal sanctions 
bias might be reduced the report said by more information for 
employers and a simpler more reliable system 
the law requires employers to complete an eligibility form for 
each newly hired worker and allows employees to establish their 
eligibility by presenting any of 17 different documents such as a 
us passport or birth certificate or an alien registration card 
ins and the labor department may inspect the forms employers 
who knowing hire unauthorized workers are subject to sanctions 
the provisions were part of an overall bill designed to reduce 
the number of illegal aliens flooding over the nations southern 
border in search of jobs concerns were raised in congress during 
debate on the bill that employers would discriminate against 
individuals who were foreign looking 
to compile data for its report the gao used methods ranging 
from surveying employers to a socalled hiring audit in conjunction 
with the urban institute in which pairs of testers went job 
hunting in chicago and san diego 
in each pair one tester appeared and sounded hispanic while the 
other did not both were equally qualified 
both testers applied for the same jobs the gao said 342 
anglo testers completed job applications while 327 hispanics 
did a total of 229 anglos received interviews compared with 172 
hispanics and 129 anglos were offered jobs compared with 85 
hispanics 
although the primary focus of the law was illegal immigration 
the gaos overall study concerned itself with discrimination based 
on national origins and not just bias against one group 
mcnary said some of the figures in the report are also soft 
because there is no base of comparison in the past he cited a 
statement within the document that some interpreters may not agree 
they own up to the fact that others may disagree and for good 
reason he said at a news conference 
his remarks brought a swift retort from officials of the 
american civil liberties union 
the gao grappled with this question very specifically and very 
carefully said lucas guttentag director of the aclu immigration 
project 
who is the commissioner to question whether the documentation 
is soft asked wade henderson associate director of the aclus 
washington office this is not the victims of discrimination who 
are complaining this is the employers themselves 
sen edward m kennedy dmass said the report confirms 
exactly what many of us in congress feared when employer sanctions 
were enacted in 1986 the sanctions would be discriminatory against 
hispanic american citizens asianamerican citizens and other 
ethnic minorities and it would be difficult to implement the law 
in a way that avoids such discrimination 
kennedy said he would introduce legislation to repeal the 
sanctions in an expedited fashion provided for under the 1986 law 
however sen alan simpson rwyo who has taken a leading role 
in writing immigration legislation expressed strong disagreement 
with the gao report 
he noted that the report found that only 66 percent of 
employers said they began not hiring job applicants whose foreign 
appearance or accent led the company to suspect they might be 
unauthorized aliens 
while that was the case the survey also found that 147 percent 
of the employers began to hire only people born in the united 
states and 13 percent stopped hiring individuals with temporary 
work eligibility documents 
</TEXT>
