<TEXT>
new yorks highest court on thursday upheld 
the manslaughter convictions of three men found guilty in the 
howard beach racial attack case 
jon lester scott kern and jason ladone had appealed their 
convictions contending their lawyers were wrongly prohibited from 
rejecting blacks as jurors in the racially charged case 
lester kern and ladone all white were convicted in december 
1987 of manslaughter assault and conspiracy for attacking three 
black men in the predominantly white howard beach section of 
queens a new york city borough in 1986 
one of the blacks 23yearold michael griffith was struck by a 
car and killed as he fled across a nearby highway another man 
cedric sandiford was beaten with tree limbs and a baseball bat 
the case before the state court of appeals centered on whether a 
1986 us supreme court ruling that prohibits prosecutors from 
excluding jurors based on race also applies to defending lawyers 
state supreme court justice thomas demakos the presiding judge in 
the howard beach case applied that standard to defense lawyers 
we agree with the courts below that such purposeful racial 
discrimination is prohibited by our state constitution said 
court of appeals judge fritz alexander in a 70 decision 
obviously were disappointed john pollok a lawyer for the 
three men said thursday he said he hadnt seen the decision but 
that he would consider asking the us supreme court to hear an 
appeal 
pollok argued before the court of appeals that prosecutors 
systematically excluded whites without giving justification to 
help gain a conviction at the same time the defense was prevented 
from doing the same with prospective black jurors he said 
as it turned out only one black was on the 12person jury 
there were also six whites three asians and two hispanics 
brooklyn district attorney charles j hynes who was appointed 
special prosecutor in the howard beach case praised thursdays 
decision 
it means that 12 judges in two separate rulings have 
unanimously affirmed that the defendants received a fair trial 
hynes said 
in criminal cases lawyers for each side may exclude a set 
number of jurors without having to give a reason however 
prosecutors may be stopped if the court believes they are rejecting 
jurors because of race in the howard beach case prosecutors asked 
that the same standard be applied to defense lawyers 
the court of appeals also rejected arguments that the three men 
were convicted with insufficient evidence 
lester was sentenced to up to 30 years in prison and is in jail 
kern was sentenced to up to 18 years and ladone up to 15 years in 
prison kern and ladone were still out on bail thursday said 
pollok 
</TEXT>
