<TEXT>
the soviet economy is heading inevitably toward 
polishstyle shock therapy to introduce a market system if 
consumers do not become so disgruntled that they block all reform 
a senior official said thursday 
vyacheslav senchagov chief of the state price committee told 
deputies of the supreme soviet that under the most radical of three 
alternatives being considered prices for raw materials and 
consumer goods are likely to rise drastically the value of the 
soviet ruble will plummet and unemployment will soar 
the government favors a more moderate approach with a transition 
period he said in remarks before his committee carried by the tass 
news agency 
but tass said senchagov acknowledged that choosing the most 
radical approach is inevitable if during the transitional period 
the populations confidence in the government does not fall so 
low as to make no reforms possible 
senchagov said the government has not yet decided which approach 
it will try to implement 
president mikhail s gorbachev said after being sworn in as the 
countrys first executive president on march 15 that his most 
important task was to take more radical steps to cure the economy 
last week a source confirmed previous news reports that 
gorbachev economists are working on a 17point program leading to a 
market system and convertibility of the soviet unions currency on 
world markets 
the source who is working on the program said soviet 
economists were encouraged by polands tough measures that went 
into effect on jan 1 but were worried they might create huge 
unemployment and the need for a vast welfare program 
the source spoke on condition of anonymity 
many reports in moscow say a radical economic shakeup will be 
put into effect this summer 
senchagovs bureaucracy sets soviet prices without regard to 
actual costs creating artificially low prices for oil and gas and 
many natural resources as well as for food and basic consumer 
goods 
but the artificially low return for soviet industry stifles 
production and initiative 
subsidies to keep prices low now cost the government the 
equivalent of onefifth the total volume of the countrys retail 
trade senchagov reported 
soviet consumers have become used to a system that offers a 
minimum of choice for low prices and many react with alarm to 
reports that the government is planning to free prices public 
concern has forced the government to delay key price reforms 
several times 
as a result of government management of prices one 
videocassette costs about twice as much as a 1200mile airline 
trip 
also the country has long told its people they have a right to 
a job but many enterprises lose money because of bloated payrolls 
polands prices have increased 1366 percent during the 12month 
period ending feb 28 the warsaw government says and more than 
200000 people are unemployed but inflation has dropped from 79 
percent in january to an estimated 6 percent in march 
poland has restocked its store shelves while soviets see their 
stores becoming emptier and emptier 
the most conservative of the three approaches in moscow would 
raise some prices for raw materials and some manufactured goods by 
fixed amounts another would free completely up to 30 percent of 
all prices set an acceptable range for other prices and control 
prices for staple goods 
under the most radical approach oil and coal prices will 
increase 35 times the number of collective and state farms known 
for their inefficiency will drop by 80 percent unprofitable 
enterprises will be closed and unemployment will increase fast 
tass quoted senchagov as saying 
the official ruble rate against convertible currencies will 
drop many times even in the most moderate plan the rubles 
value will be cut in half 
a ruble now ranges in value from 159 for locals in the soviet 
union to about 16 cents when foreigners exchange their hard 
currency 
