<TEXT>
portauprince haiti ap about 10000 demonstrators shouting 
justice and democracy rallied at city hall on thursday to 
celebrate the restoration of haitis suspended 1987 constitution 
the new civilian government of president ertha pascaltrouillot 
announced wednesday it was restoring nearly all articles of the 
constitution a national holiday was declared for thursday the 
third anniversary of the constitutions ratification in a popular 
vote 
the government said it restored all but a few unspecified 
articles of the constitution dealing with certain government 
functions including those of parliament because no lawmaking body 
is in place 
the restored constitution turns the police force over to control 
by a civilian justice minister the force is now incorporated into 
the army 
mrs pascaltrouillot was named provisional president march 13 
after military ruler lt gen prosper avril fled the country during 
a popular uprising 
the constitution is stronger than bayonets said the rev 
antoine adrien spokesman for the unity assembly a coalition of 
political parties that called the rally 
we have taken a giant step forward even though we do not have 
a just society yet said adrien speaking on a platform next to 
other political leaders in front of city hall in portauprince 
the capital 
the twohour rally was peaceful schools and shops were closed 
for the demonstration the first authorized by police in more than 
18 months 
the constitution ratified by 99 percent of the voters march 29 
1987 was suspended by thendictator lt gen henri namphy in july 
1988 it was partially restored by avril in march 1989 
the demonstrators thursday also protested against the political 
violence that has terrorized the population of this impoverished 
caribbean nation since avrils ouster 
demonstrators carried cardboard signs bearing such slogans as 
arrest all criminals and justice now one group of youths 
hoisted a marcher on their shoulders and put a tire around his body 
in a mock lynching 
from march 18 to march 23 nearly 40 people were killed and 
dozens wounded in a rash of crimes allegedly provoked by opponents 
of democracy and avril supporters 
the government wednesday ordered all paramilitary agents to hand 
over their weapons to police within 72 hours or face prosecution 
the dreaded paramilitary thugs known as tonton macoutes were 
outlawed after dictator jeanclaude baby doc duvalier was 
forced from power by another popular uprising in february 1986 
however many former tonton macoutes were integrated into the army 
as special agents and have often been accused of statesponsored 
terrorism 
mrs pascaltrouillot did not attend thursdays rally for 
security reasons said social affairs minister claudette werleigh 
she has promised to hold free elections as soon as possible 
