<TEXT>
the medellin cocaine cartel hinted 
thursday it will retaliate for the governments renewed extradition 
of drug suspects to the united states 
the cartels message came in a communique a day after the 
government of president virgilio barco sent 29yearold fernando 
gutierrez to arizona for trial on drugtrafficking and 
moneylaundering charges it was the first extradition of a drug 
trafficking suspect since jan 21 
the cartel which has been waging a war with the government 
claimed thursday it had been betrayed by officials who started and 
then backed out of talks aimed at a settlement to a bloody conflict 
that has left more than 200 colombians dead since the august 
slaying of a presidential candidate 
accusing the police of murdering suspects the group said we 
will not remain indifferent in the face of betrayal torture and 
killing of our companions it did not elaborate 
it again called extraditions illegal and attacks against 
colombian sovereignty 
the traffickers communique given to medellin news media was 
signed by the extraditables the name adopted by the medellin 
cartel 
the government has been using extraditions feared by the 
traffickers as a weapon in its usbacked war with traffickers 
extradition is considered necessary because traffickers often 
evade colombian justice by killing and bribing judges gutierrez 
was the 15th colombian extradited since august and police are 
holding 17 more colombians wanted by the united states 
in a statement thursday barco said the government this year had 
captured 845 drug suspects and seized more than 19000 pounds of 
cocaine other seizures include 31 million in cash 387 pounds of 
gold and about 21000 pounds of dynamite 
on jan 17 the cartel declared a unilateral truce it said it 
was prepared to surrender to the government in exchange for an end 
to extradition 
speculation about possible talks between the government and 
traffickers increased during the last two months because no one 
else was extradited 
that speculation peaked sunday when interior minister carlos 
lemos simmonds resigned he said the government had lost its will 
to fight the traffickers 
in thursdays communique the cartel said two businessmen acted 
as intermediaries in the talks it said they were received by barco 
on various occasions to negotiate the release of the son of the 
presidents closest adviser german montoya 
the cartel kidnapped alvaro montoya on dec 20 and released him 
on jan 23 in one of a series of what it called goodwill gestures 
to show the government its desire for peace 
barco denied thursday that the government had negotiated with 
traffickers and said it would continue fighting the criminals 
there has not been nor will there be official nor 
extraofficial contacts between the government and representatives 
of drug traffickers much less pacts treaties and agreements 
between the government and drug traffickers barco said in his 
communique thursday 
barco acknowledged that the businessman had been received but 
he called it an informal gathering without official status 
the cartel communique claimed that while the government was 
negotiating with traffickers it sent police death squads to wipe 
them out the cartel accused police of murdering 40 of its members 
the barco administration took more action thursday against 
traffickers declaring martial law in a medellin area township that 
is reportedly controlled by medellin cartel leader pablo escobar 
the move allows a military administrator to take over policing 
power from the popularly elected mayor of envigado 
</TEXT>
