said rep greg stumbo the majority floor leader were not going 
to be a follower anymore were going to be a leader 
the bill repeals and replaces all kentucky laws on elementary 
and secondary education the kentucky supreme court last year 
declared the entire school system unconstitutional because its 
quality varied so greatly between rich school districts and poor 
the court found that kentucky students were performing in the 
lowest quarter nationally as measured by standardized tests 
the legislation will mean more money for schools in general and 
dramatically greater funding for poor districts it also calls for 
a largescale investment in technology emphasis on early childhood 
education and extra help for potential dropouts 
under the current system spending for the states 570000 
students varies from 1800 to 4200 a year per student depending 
on the district under the new plan the minimum spending level 
would be 2900 in the 199091 school year overall state financing 
for elementary and secondary education would increase from 15 
billion this year to 19 billion next year 
under the plan local districts will gain more control over 
daytoday operations of schools which are to be judged by how 
successfully their students learn cash rewards will await 
employees of schools that improve each year 
in addition control of the system would be shifted from an 
elected state superintendent to an appointed education commissioner 
about half of the money from the tax increase would be spent on 
schools the senates most important amendment would eliminate 
immediately the state deduction that residents receive for federal 
tax payments raising 141 million in the next two years the house 
version of the bill would have phased out the deduction 
the governor hailed the senates passage of the bill wednesday 
as history in the making 
