<TEXT>
antinarcotics inspectors now supervise 
cultivation of opium poppies which have grown on the dusty 
anatolian plain for 5000 years that pleases narcotics police but 
farmers say theyre losing money 
in 1971 poppy production was halted by a militarycontrolled 
government under pressure from the united states to cut the supply 
of opium to heroin traffickers 
cultivation resumed in 1974 after civilian rule was restored 
with controls intended to restrict production to pharmaceutical use 
us and turkish narcotics police praise the system which they 
say is smuggleproof a small army of inspectors makes sure the 
crop is used exclusively for medical purposes and does not make its 
way to traffickers 
farmers do not share the official pleasure they say the program 
costs them money 
in the old days we could marry off two sons in one season 
with the earnings from our poppy fields said halil altimtas 
headman of ozburnu village in bolvadin township now the bride 
prices are up but the price for poppies remains too low 
just as the current us battle against cocaine focuses on south 
american coca leaves turkish poppies were the target of an 
antiheroin campaign in the late 1960s and early 1970s 
the united states claimed at least half the heroin reaching its 
territory originated in the poppy fields spread across seven 
provinces of central turkey 
most problems encountered since the new system took effect in 
1974 have to do with production and pricing 
us narcotics officials say no heroin from the turkish poppy 
crop has been discovered on the illicit market 
one important reason is that farmers must use the poppy 
straw harvesting method instead of slitting the tangerinesized 
pods to let opium gum ooze out the method used for heroin they 
let the pods dry in the fields 
morphine derivatives used as painkillers can be extracted from 
dried poppies only in a sophisticated alkaloids plant 
turkey spent 90 million to build the worlds largest and most 
advanced alkaloids factory 150 miles southwest of ankara the 
capital in the heart of the poppygrowing region 
over a decade while the factory was being built the government 
paid another 15 million to farmers whose poppies it was legally 
obligated to buy 
about 76000 tons of unprocessed pods piled up in storage 
because it was difficult to export something of such light weight 
and great bulk that kept the factory going at full capacity for 
four years 
low official prices for the poppy pods discouraged cultivation 
and the plant was in full production by 1986 the turkish alkaloids 
board captured more than half the us market and 40 percent of the 
world market for morphine and codeine and earned about 10 million 
a year 
the good times did not last the plant has been idle since 
december for lack of pods to process 
last years pod crop was only 3000 tons because of autumn 
drought winter frost and the unwillingness of farmers to grow 
poppies for the equivalent of 14 cents for a kilogram 22 pounds 
of dried pods 
india is the only other legal producer of poppies on a large 
scale but australia recently entered the market the united states 
supports the control efforts of india and turkey with a pledge to 
buy 80 percent of its needs from them 
demand for morphine and its derivatives is not flexible and 
averages about 200 tons a year competition is fierce and the price 
has dropped to about 180 a kilogram it was 800 when turkey drew 
the plans for its factory 
the government tripled its price for pods this year to encourage 
growers but attila yildirim manager of the akaloids plant said 
paying too much could put turkey at a competitive disadvantage 
farmers and officials agree the poppy is the most suitable cash 
crop for the sandy soil of the arid anatolian plain 
yildirim and officials of the state soil products office are 
proud of their security arrangements 
about 600 inspectors aided by reconnaissance planes keep track 
of the fields to prevent unlicensed cultivation or slitting of pods 
for opium gum 
morphine is stored behind steel doors at the alkaloids plant 
armored trucks with military and police excorts carry the products 
to cargo planes 
this place is better protected and less accesible to outsiders 
than most military bases yildirim said 
</TEXT>
