<TEXT>
the government says having many 
children is a womans patriotic duty but decades of large families 
have overloaded the school system and created a serious 
unemployment threat 
in the 1950s the communist government set out to increase the 
population of mongolias 930000 square miles by offering money and 
special privileges to couples with more than four children 
in other countries the population policy is to keep it at 
the same level or to keep it low but mongolia is different 
navch head of the government demography department said in an 
interview 
we have a small population she said thats why we have 
such a policy 
mongolias population was 649300 when it became independent in 
1921 it experienced a baby boom in the 1960s and 1970s and the 
birthrate peaked in 1963 at 43 per thousand people well over the 
19801985 world averge of 277 births per thousand 
by 1989 government incentives combined with better living 
conditions and health care had raised the population to 209 
million 
yanjinsuren a 46yearold herdswoman who lives outside ulan 
bator the capital has 10 children ranging in age from 28 to 2 
i like babies she said i think its lucky to have many 
children im a working woman but still the mongolian family and 
mongolian traditions are the most important thing 
mothers with more than four children receive 133 to 1033 
annually for each child under 16 depending on the childs age and 
the total number of children 
those with more than five children get a medal and the title 
mother of the second degree and a woman with eight or more 
children is a mother of the first degree the records say 
92600 women received medals and titles in 1988 
encouraging large families had unforeseen results nursery 
schools can accommodate only one child in six and kindergartens 
only one in three the communist party newspaper unen reported 
three shifts operate at some schools in ulan bator where 
onefourth of all mongolians live the paper said and only 21 
percent of the nations doctors are pediatricians 
unemployment is a major potential problem about 50 percent of 
mongolians are under age 18 and will create a glut when they enter 
the labor market unless the economy grows more rapidly 
now our policy is not just increasing the population but also 
to raise the quality of the population said gerel head of the 
population bureau we have to look at the labor force and balance 
everything 
a new health law that took effect in january gives women the 
right to decide how many children they will have and when 
it makes abortions free to all and lengthens maternity leave 
from nine months to two years abortions previously were restricted 
to women over 35 with four or more children 
many younger women balk at raising large families and feel they 
can show their patriotism in other ways 
navch 35 has a 12yearold daughter and a son of 9 she does 
not intend to have more 
thats enough she said after 35 its too old 
a recent survey found that 57 percent of women questioned 
thought four was the ideal number of children last year the 
average number of children per woman of childbearing age was 48 
down from seven 20 years ago 
baasay 44 a herdswoman with eight children said a married 
daughter told her recently she wanted only two 
two is okay baasay said the times are different the 
family is different young women dont want many children 
</TEXT>
