<TEXT>
sweeping changes in the world political 
order and localized conflicts such as panama and the persian gulf 
are prompting swift wholesale revision of the lessons being taught 
at americas advanced military colleges 
at the naval war college the nations oldest such institution 
officials say 98 of the 145 readings assigned to students last fall 
no longer are on the list for the third trimester that began this 
month 
thats just one measure of the changes that are taking 
place said william e turcotte a former naval officer who heads 
the schools national security decision making department and is a 
key planner of its curriculum 
as the morning fog rolls in from narragansett bay the 360 
students at the nwc are focusing their attention on 
contingencies military scenarios involving us forces in a 
role far more constricted and less predictable than the 
natowarsaw pact showdown that has been the basis of military 
doctrine for 40 years 
increasingly say officials of the college their curriculum and 
war gaming will stress urban warfare terrorism and low 
intensity crises in which the united states interests are 
ambiguous and its capacity to act is affected by special political 
or geographical factors 
students also will be asked to consider monetary costs a factor 
the officials say has not figured significantly in classroom 
discussions before 
the cost of military operations is one of many questions that 
must be examined in a new light turcotte said 
this year will be especially traumatic for the students but 
its also a great time for the students a very dynamic period in 
which they will be as close to the problems as the major policy 
advisers the congress and the press he said 
turcotte also said that for the schools faculty experts the 
supposed end of the cold war is doing much more than simply 
altering their lesson plans 
never have we spent so much time trying to learn for ourselves 
whats happening he said but it is the most exciting time 
that ive ever been in the classroom here 
the naval war college founded in 1884 in this picturesque 
seaport famed as a summer resort of the superrich is one of a 
halfdozen colleges run by the defense department to provide 
advanced schooling in military and political subjects for career 
officers government officials and other selected individuals 
including military officers from other countries 
while each school is mainly concerned with the mission of one 
branch of the armed forces the pentagons policy of jointness 
in military affairs means faculty and students are drawn from all 
services 
thus a typical nwc seminar of 15 to 20 students might be led by 
a civilian or an army officer and include officers from the navy 
army air force marines and coast guard 
turcotte who has taught at the nwc since 1974 said curriculum 
changes reflecting political upheavals in the soviet bloc actually 
began last summer and the first trimester ended just as the berlin 
wall was starting to crumble in november 
in place of the cold war doctrines spawned by four decades of 
tension between the two superpowers the revised program will 
concentrate on the types of crises that might now arise and how 
us strategy and forces should be designed to deal with them 
in any contingency we are most likely to have the preponderant 
force but the objectives are confusing said turcotte we will 
win but the nature of how we win and what we leave behind is 
complex there are a lot of dark alleys in contingencies 
among new issues to be examined he said are such questions as 
whether smaller countries freed from superpower influence become 
less stable and more aggressive toward their neighbors and whether 
the united states can or should continue to press japan and germany 
to spend more on selfdefense as washington cuts its military costs 
and the two germanys draw closer together 
the persian gulf where the navy conducted a major operation in 
198788 to safeguard commercial shipping endangered by the 
iraqiran war offers an important case study a regional conflict 
in which the united states is not directly involved but has 
crucial interests to protect 
another model for the classroom was provided by the bush 
administrations invasion of panama which nwc officials said 
raised not only political issues but moral and practical questions 
about the conduct of urban warfare in which civilian lives are at 
risk 
they also cite the proliferation of missiles and other modern 
technology possibly even nuclear weapons among smaller nations 
the question of whether us military forces should be used in drug 
interdiction and the lack of an effective policy on terrorism and 
hostagetaking 
turcotte said the changes in europe have led nato to extend its 
presumed warning time for a soviet attack from several days to six 
months but might also increase the relative importance of 
strategic nuclear forces which remain in place and moscows 
internal security forces 
</TEXT>
