water managers have joined the 
fight against the thirsty melaleuca tree an australian import that 
in less than a decade may take over threequarters of the 
everglades 
wiping out the tree will take more than 10 million and as long 
as 25 years a task force has concluded and the souh florida water 
management district governing board has provided 75000 for the 
first years work 
introduced in 1906 by a university of miami forestry professor 
who saw it as a potential timber source the melaleuca had no 
natural enemies 
scientists believe it infests 625 square miles more than 60 
square miles of that an area nearly as big as washington dc 
is solid melaleuca the report says 
the tree overwhelms habitats disrupts food chains and takes 
three to six times as much water as sawgrass and other plants it 
burns hot and spreads its seeds after fires it also has a foul 
odor and may cause respiratory problems 
the task force has suggested using chemicals for now and 
eventually introducing insects that are its natural enemies but 
there is concern the bugs could become as much a threat as the 
trees they kill 
the task force concedes the tree will never be eradicated its 
goal is to stop its spread and manage it 
the tree thrives in warm climates with infrequent frosts 
tolerates a range of soils and water qualities and can grow in 
flooded and dry areas the melaleuca is identified by a papery bark 
and white flowers that look like bottle brushes 
