after failing to find a buyer since the 1987 stock market crash 
the 105yearold firm once the nations ninthlargest 
brokerage said the filing was long anticipated the firm 
stopped doing business eight months ago after selling most of its 
operations 
wednesdays filing in us bankruptcy court freezes pending 
legal action against the collapsed wall street house and places 
other contentious issues in liquidating the firm under the auspices 
of a federal judge 
thomson mckinnon listed 89 million in assets and 139 million 
in liabilities in filing for protection from creditors 
last july the firm sold its retail brokerage offices and 
customer accounts to prudentialbache securities corp for about 
60 million that deal followed the collapse of a proposed merger 
of the two firms that would have created one of the largest 
securities houses on wall street 
since then thomson mckinnon has sold its seats on the nations 
stock and commodity exchanges but it still needs to liquidate part 
of its securities portfolio and other assets 
it became apparent that we were at a point where we could do 
better if we have the assistance and protection of the bankruptcy 
court said donald g mccabe thomson mckinnon general counsel 
brokerage firms generally are not permitted to seek chapter 11 
protection voluntarily but thomson mckinnon officials said the 
filing was allowed because the firm no longer had active accounts 
and most of its holdings had been liquidated 
the firm has been liquidating under the auspices of the 
securities and exchange commission and the securities investor 
protection corp the officials said both agencies endorsed the 
bankruptcy filing 
the securities firm has been reduced to about 100 employees from 
4700 before the prudentialbache deal mccabe said 
thomson mckinnon said it lost 337 million in 1987 and 385 
million in 1988 in addition to stock and bond losses the company 
said losses from a real estate investment trust heightened its need 
for a buyer 
the bankruptcy filing names commonwealth bank of australia as 
its largest unsecured creditor owed 275 million from a 
subordinated loan the second largest claim is an 11 million 
subordinated loan from hill samuel bank of london 
the filing also says thomson mckinnon wants to segregate 22 
million in assets for the accounts of former customers 
several classaction lawsuits filed on behalf of former thomson 
mckinnon employees recently were consolidated in federal court in 
new york they allege broad financial mismanagement including 
buying apartments and a yacht with company assets at least one 
suit seeks 100 million in damages 
under federal law all legal action against the brokerage unit 
is suspended during bankruptcy proceedings the lawsuits though 
also name the parent company thomson mckinnon inc and that 
action can proceed 
the parent still is seeking to liquidate all its assets the 
company said in a statement that its efforts are focused on 
attempting to sell its 63 percent interest in its other operating 
entity thomson mckinnon asset management lp 
that unit a mutual fund and private account money manager for 
67 billion in assets is not affected by the bankruptcy filing 
it has operated as a separate entity since a public stock offering 
in 1987 
</TEXT>
