<TEXT>
japanese business executives once thought they 
could solve their image problems in the united states by making 
corporate charitable donations and hiring lobbyists to represent 
them in washington 
now in response to accusations that tokyo has been buying 
support from us officials and academics some japanese protest 
what they call a japanlobby hunt reminiscent of mccarthyist 
anticommunist campaigns 
the criticism they say is souring constructive ties between 
the worlds two largest economic powers 
why pick on us the consultants and lawyers who have the 
misfortune of representing a currently unpopular ally are the very 
people that senior business executives and government officials in 
japan have lent an ear to said kazuo nukazawa managing director 
of keidanren or the federation of economic organizations japans 
most powerful business group 
todays trade policy mccarthyites seem determined to ostracize 
those scarce few who have experience and expertise on the country 
the us has serious business negotiations with he wrote in a 
recent commentary in the japan times newspaper 
other japanese also express frustration over accusations in the 
united states that many american trade negotiators and scholars are 
suspiciously vulnerable to japanese influence 
the debate was created largely by a jan 22 article in the new 
republic a prominent american magazine titled the japanese 
megaphone tokyos americans that say yes 
in it author john b judis wrote that the hundreds of millions 
of dollars funneled by japanese corporations to us think tanks 
and lobbyists are tilting the debate about americas economic 
future without the public being aware of it 
japan has assembled a virtual whos who of lobbyists and 
advisers in washington judis wrote this army of lobbyists and 
advisers furnishes japanese companies with the troops necessary to 
win battles in washington 
such charges have generated a japanologist hunt reminiscent 
of a mccarthyist red hunt tetsuya shibayama wrote in a recent 
issue of the weekly asahi journal alluding to sen joseph 
mccarthys diatribes over what he saw as communist subversion of 
the us government circles in the 1950s 
shibayama blamed the problem on what he calls japanese ignorance 
of exactly how their wealth and power are perceived overseas 
one of japans top authorities on the issue agrees 
japanese companies spare no expense to hire big names but 
often their money is wasted said masatake takahashi a 
commentator who has published several books on lobbying in the 
united states 
i keep telling executives of companies they should be more 
selective theyre being criticized mainly because their approach 
is wrong you have to know how to use lobbyists properly or its 
not worth the trouble and expense he said 
japanese officials at several major companies declined to 
comment on the issue 
our activities are mainly community oriented we commit 01 
percent of our total sales to grassroots activities and we make 
academic contributions to professorships at top universities but 
we have no particular comment on lobbying activities said akira 
nagano spokesman at matsushita electronic industrial co maker of 
