<TEXT>
mobil corp targeted by environmentalists for 
alleged misleading advertising said thursday it no longer will 
refer to its hefty trash bags as degradable 
but the head of a task force of state attorneys general 
investigating deceptive advertising and packaging by mobil and 
other companies claimed the oil giant merely was trying to deflect 
potential liability ahead of a scheduled negotiating session next 
week 
people need to know this didnt come out of the blue said 
hubert humphrey iii minnesotas attorney general it comes as 
the result of a meeting two weeks ago with state and federal 
agencies that are very much looking at enforcement action 
mobil has been criticized for advertising on its hefty trash 
bags that claims the product decomposes after exposure to 
elements like sun wind and rain 
environmentalists say the reference to degradability is 
misleading because more than 80 percent of trash bags are not 
exposed to sunlight long enough to degrade but end up in dry 
landfills that rarely are exposed to sunlight 
in thursdays announcement mobil said its chemical division 
would continue making hefty trash bags with an environmentally 
safe additive that speeds their decomposition when exposed to 
sunlight but the company will delete the references to 
degradability on the packaging 
mobil spokesman allen gray said mobil chemical co was taking 
the action in response to mounting confusion regarding the 
definition of degradability 
gray conceded that if left out in arizona somewhere a bag 
with the additive can quickly decompose in a couple of months but 
in a northern climate like chicago it could take well over a year 
nontheless gray said claims that the bags degrade in sunlight 
have been fully substantiated by tests and that the company 
never said the bags would be the answer to the countrys waste 
disposal problem 
humphrey and other task force members said mobils action could 
send a signal to other companies making similar claims 
this retreat by mobil however admirable is just the opening 
victory for new york and other states in our war over dishonest 
advertising claims about the environmental benefits of certain 
products robert abrams new yorks attorney general said in a 
prepared statement 
gray said the company began marketing the degradable bags 
because of competitive pressures he said the phaseout of the 
labeling was expected to take several months 
mobil officials are scheduled to meet monday in st louis with 
legal representatives from the eightstate task force including 
california massachusetts minnesota missouri new york texas 
washington and wisconsin humphrey said mobil may be subject to 
fines or further injunctive relief including a binding legal 
agreement to halt similar advertising on other mobil products such 
as styrofoam plates and plastic grocery bags 
officials from the federal trade commission which joined the 
investigation earlier this month are expected to attend the 
meeting said ed barbini spokesman for abrams 
ftc chairman janet steiger said earlier this month the agency 
had joined the task force to determine whether environmental claims 
made by various products from trash bags to hair spray could be 
substantiated 
no other companies have been named by the task force or the ftc 
although several companies are under investigation 
