discount stockbroker quick amp reilly inc said 
thursday it had raised commissions by about 5 a trade in order to 
provide new services for customers 
thomas quick president of the firm said the 8 percent increase 
was not prompted by the downturn in the retail brokerage industry 
stemming from the october 1987 stock market crash 
quick said the new yorkbased firm recently installed a 24hour 
telephone stock quote system for investors in 25 cities and added 
free checkwriting privileges for money market account clients 
these things cost money quick said in light of inflation 
we didnt feel we were really being piggies 
he said the nations third largest discount brokerage had not 
raised its commissions since 1983 the move left quick amp reilly 
commissions still slightly lower than the leaders in the field san 
franciscobased charles schwab amp co and bostonbased fidelity 
investments 
charles schwab last raised its commissions by 6 percent in 
february 1988 and said it has no plans for another increase a 
spokesman for fidelity could not be reached for comment 
under the change at quick amp reilly which took effect monday 
individual investors will be charged according to the principal 
amount of a transaction before quick amp reilly calculated 
commissions based on the number of shares bought or sold and the 
price per share 
quick said while the average commission was 5 a trade charges 
would be higher for trades involving small principal amounts and 
lower for transactions involving high principals 
quick amp reilly on wednesday reported its fourthquarter profits 
rose to 252 million or 27 cents a share for the period ended 
feb 28 from 209 million or 22 cents per share in the same 
period a year ago revenue rose to 283 million from 221 million 
for its full fiscal year quick amp reillys profit increased 
about 15 percent to 114 million or 121 a share from 997 
million or 105 a share revenue climbed to 106 million from 
776 million a year earlier 
discount brokers have reported healthier profits than large wall 
street firms despite a decline in stock trading activity since the 
stock market crash disounts have low expenses and benefit from 
high business volume because of their relatively lower commission 
rates 
</TEXT>
