<TEXT>
lockheed corp chairman daniel tellep 
promised major concessions to big shareholders thursday but 
predicted victory in his battle with texas investor harold simmons 
over control of the company 
im expecting a clear majority in every category of 
shareholder except of course mr simmons tellep said at a news 
conference after the aerospace companys annual meeting 
simmons who owns 19 percent of lockheed and his chief 
strategist j landis martin said they believed the contest was 
too close to call although martin later seemed to acknowledge they 
had lost 
its like a political campaign he said sometimes you 
just have to come back again the next time 
simmons however claimed victory in pressuring tellep to make 
concessions to the concerns of big investors seeking more input in 
running the company 
i think we achieved an awful lot simmons said claiming he 
also forced lockheed to concentrate on profits rather than merely 
increasing the amount of business the company does 
lockheed spent about 8 million on the proxy battle while 
simmons said he spent about 6 million both sides said they wished 
they had not had to do so 
it was a tremendous drain of energy away from running the 
company tellep told reporters 
during the meeting held in a giant hangar adjacent to burbank 
airport tellep told shareholders that he met with 70 institutional 
investors during the proxy war over the past two weeks and that he 
considered it his baptism by fire and a highly valuable 
experience 
concessions were forced by big pension funds and other 
institutional shareholders many of which defected to simmons who 
sought to replace lockheeds board with his representatives 
simmons slate included john tower former head of the senate 
armed services committee and retired adm elmo r zumwalt jr the 
former chief of naval operations and former member of the joint 
chiefs of staff 
preliminary voting results may be available next week 
tellep told the meeting he believes in shareholder democracy 
and offered several future concessions including secret votes if 
that is what a significant number of shareholders want 
other promises included 
a provision to opt out of strict antitakeover provisions of 
law in delaware where lockheed is incorporated tellep said that 
even if the provision did not pass but there was a significant 
minority vote for it he would recommend that the board support an 
amendment at the next meeting to have lockheed opt out 
a promise that he would ask for a list of possible shareholder 
representatives to lockheeds 15person board and would select up 
to three directors from that list he earlier offered to select 
only one 
an offer to meet regularly with representatives of simmons nl 
industries inc to discuss the future of lockheed 
martin and simmons objected to the way in which some of the 
shares belonging to an employees stock ownership plan had been 
voted they said the trustee of the plan which holds 19 percent of 
lockheed stock had wrongly voted all the shares even though about 
30 percent of the employees failed to vote 
the 30 percent was voted in proportion with the rest of the 
plans votes which lockheed announced late thursday had gone for 
tellep by more than 90 percent martin suggested that if they lost 
by a narrow margin the result might be challenged on those grounds 
simmons contends that lockheed with a recent history of sagging 
earnings and underestimating costs of developing new programs must 
insist on better profits at its noncore businesses or sell them 
the company portrays simmons as a corporate raider intent on 
personal profit with no knowledge of how to run lockheed the 
nations sixthlargest defense contractor with 1989 sales of 99 
billion 
simmons who has lost 100 million on his 530 million 
investment in lockheed stock insists he can better focus the 
company and has a good record of profitably running companies he 
purchases including nl industries amalgamated sugar co and 
keystone steel and wire co 
during the meeting simmons and martin were bombarded with 
questions from lockheed employees and shareholders worried that 
simmons might want to merely dismantle the company for his own 
benefit 
the most vigorous defense of tellep by an employee came from bob 
strickland a worker at lockheed aircraft services in ontario 
mr tellep and i have one thing in common a great love for 
our company lockheed has always been there for me and now i feel 
its my duty to be there for him strickland said about voting 
his 38 shares for the current board 
historically few proxy battles have succeeded in unseating 
directors however analysts say simmons made strong inroads into 
the ranks of the institutional investors who hold 60 percent of 
lockheeds shares 
simmons chief coup was persuading californias huge public 
employees pension fund known as calpers to vote its nearly 1 
percent of lockheed shares for him said lawrence harris a 
securities analyst at the bateman eichler hill richards brokerage 
in los angeles 
calpers has led institutional investors in pressing for more 
control over companies they own 
